etymologies: mid 19th century; earliest use found in William Macgillivray (1796–1852), ornithologist and natural historian. From multi- + classical Latin iugātus, after French multijuguées, plural

definitions: Of a leaf: having more than one pair of leaflets.
Designating or relating to phyllotaxis (or an analogous arrangement of flowers) in which the parastichy ratios are divisible by a common factor; characterized or produced by several genetic spirals.
